# Windows Command Execution Rules (CoreUtils Enhanced)
- You are running commands inside a Windows `cmd.exe` environment, but Windows CoreUtils is installed.
- You CAN and SHOULD use standard Linux/GNU commands directly (such as `find`, `grep`, `cat`, `head`, `tail`, `ls`, `rm`, `cp`, `mv`).
- ALWAYS prefix your command string with `chcp 65001 >nul &&` to force UTF-8 encoding and prevent Chinese characters from turning into garbled text.
- Do NOT use heavy `powershell -Command` wrappers unless standard commands or CoreUtils cannot achieve the task.
- **CRITICAL (xargs Path Backslash Issue):** NEVER use raw `find ... | xargs grep` in Windows `cmd.exe`. Windows paths contain backslashes (`\`), which `xargs` will interpret as escape characters and strip away, resulting in "file not found" errors. Instead, use `find -exec`, `grep -rl`, or `find -print0 | xargs -0`.

[Bad Examples]
# Bad: Heavy PowerShell wrapper (unnecessary)
powershell -Command "Get-ChildItem -Path 'build' -Recurse | Where-Object { $_.Name -like '*.exe' }"

# Bad: Fails in Windows because xargs strips path backslashes, making grep look for ".srceffectsmain.h"
chcp 65001 >nul && find . -name "*.h" | xargs grep -l "using RegistryPaths ="

[Good Examples - Cleaner and Faster]
# Good: Simple file finding
chcp 65001 >nul && find build/audacity-release -name "*.exe"

# Good (Alternative 1): Using find -exec to safely handle Windows paths without xargs
chcp 65001 >nul && find . -name "*.h" -exec grep -l "using RegistryPaths =" {} +

# Good (Alternative 2): Using direct recursive grep which bypasses find entirely
chcp 65001 >nul && grep -rl --include="*.h" "using RegistryPaths =" .

# Good (Alternative 3): Using -print0 and xargs -0 to disable escape character processing
chcp 65001 >nul && find . -name "*.h" -print0 | xargs -0 grep -l "using RegistryPaths ="